suppressPackageStartupMessages({
  library(GenomicRanges)

options(timeout = 6000)
download.file("https://ethz-ins.org/content/w10.assignment.zip", "w10.assignment.zip")
unzip("w10.assignment.zip")
peaks <- list.files(pattern="bed$")
# we first import the peaks
peaks <- lapply(peaks, rtracklayer::import.bed)
# we'll focus on the high-quality peaks
peaks <- lapply(peaks, FUN=function(x) x[x$score>800])
# we get the union of non-redundant regions
regions <- reduce(unlist(GRangesList(peaks)))


tracks <- list.files(pattern="bw$")

Plot

ml <- signal2Matrix(tracks, regions, extend=2000)

Plotting the singal for each cluster, biggest difference seems to be in cluster 3, with Creb1 and Creb3L1 having a lot more signal than Creb3, differences in cluster 1 and 3 seem to be smaller

Clustering using relative signal instead:

cl_relative <- clusterSignalMatrices(ml, k=3, scaleRows = TRUE)
##   ~80% of the variance explained by clusters
d <- meltSignals(ml, splitBy=cl_relative)
ggplot(d, aes(position, mean, colour=sample)) + geom_line() + facet_wrap(~split)

plotEnrichedHeatmaps(ml, row_split = cl_relative, scale_rows = "global", mean_color=mycolors)

### Cluster 3

ggplot(head(bp[["Cluster 3"]],15), aes(Hyper_Fold_Enrichment, reorder(name, Hyper_Adjp_BH), size=Hyper_Foreground_Region_Hits, color=-log10(Hyper_Adjp_BH))) + geom_point() + scale_color_viridis_c()

According to the GO term of their biological function, there seems to be a clear difference in the specific biological function of the different TFs. Cluster 2, in which Creb3 dominated, is predominantly enriched for immune function and cell signaling. Cluster 3, which was dominated by Creb3L1 and to a lesser extend Creb1, is predominantly enriched in processes related to transcription, translation, mRNA splicing and stability, and chromatin remodelling. Cluster 1, which was almost exclusively bound by Creb1, there seems to be a strong enrichment for developmental processes and morphogenesis.

It should be noted that for Cluster 3 the adjusted P values are not significant, so it can only be seen as exploratory data. To make decisive claims, more data should be analyzed. Could for exmaple be repeated with whole genome.
